Project presentation

This project applies supervised machine learning techniques to a airline dataset in order to predict passenger satisfaction regarding different airlines and traveling.

The data contains structured numerical and categorical variables describing different aspects of flight experience. The dataset contains 23 variables (such as seat comfort, onboard service, food quality, delays etc.) and more than 130,000 observations. It is already splitted into two different sets:

  • A train dataset with 104,000 observations (80%)
  • A test dataset with 26,000 observations (20%)

The objective is to understand how these factors influence overall passenger satisfaction and to build a classification model that can predict whether a passenger is satisfied or not regarding its flight experience.

The target variable will then be passenger satisfaction, a binary outcome indicating whether a passenger is satisfied or dissatisfied.

All other variables are used as independant variables (features) to explain and predict this outcome. Since the task involves a binary target variable, the problem will be formulated as a supervised classification machine learning problem.

Plan of the notebook :

First, an exploratory data analysis is conducted to better understand the dataset, explore variable distributions, and identify potential relationships between the features and the target variable.

Next, the data is preprocessed, including encoding of categorical variables, feature scaling where necessary, and a train test split (which is already done with the imported dataset, 80/20%).

Finally, classification models will be trained and evaluated. A random forest model will be applied to capture complex relationships. We will then compute the model's performance using standard evaluation metrics such as the confusion matrix, accuracy, and ROC AUC, before drawing final conclusions.

Preprossessing

We will start by identifying and encoding the target variable satisfaction

In[98]:
train_df["target"] = train_df["satisfaction"].map(

test_df["target"] = test_df["satisfaction"].map(
    {"satisfied": 1, "neutral or dissatisfied": 0}
)

Then we clearly identify training and testing datas, and we seperate X and Y (independant vs target variable(s)) on both training and testing datas.

y_test = test_df["target"]

Here variables are first identified based on their data types. Categorical features are encoded using one hot, while numerical features are passed through unchanged. This ensures that all input variables are represented in a numerical format compatible with our ML model.

In[101]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer

categorical_features = X_train.select_dtypes(include="object").columns
numerical_features = X_train.select_dtypes(exclude="object").columns

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ("cat", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore"), categorical_features),
        ("num", "passthrough", numerical_features)
    ]
)

Then we apply the preprocessor to the training and test data

In[102]:
# Apply preprocessing
X_train_processed = preprocessor.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_processed = preprocessor.transform(X_test)

Now the preprocessing part is done. Our datas are correctly encoded, we can move onto the random forest part.

Random Forest as a first model

The random forest model is trained using hyperparameters that balance model flexibility, robustness, and computational cost.

As we saw during the courses, if a sufficiently large number of trees is used to reduce variance and stabilize predictions, the maximum tree depth is controlled to limit overfitting by preventing individual trees from becoming overly complex.

The max_features parameter is set to its standard value for classification to increase diversity among trees.

These choices follow common best practices discussed in the course and were confirmed through consultation with a generative AI assistant (chatgpt), to choose a particular depth here.

Hyperparameters can be later refined.

In[105]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

rf = RandomForestClassifier(
    n_estimators=100,
    max_depth=8,
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=-1
)

rf.fit(X_train_processed, y_train)

Model is now trained, let's check its performances. After testing n_estimators = 300, without any max_depth, the training AUC was 1 and the testing was 99.8. Since the training was obvisuly overfitted, i decided to limit the max_depth at 8 with only 100 estimators. The respective testing/training AUC are still extremely high, but also extremely close. Therefore, i decided to stick to that model.

Model's performance test

In[106]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

# Train performance
y_train_proba = rf.predict_proba(X_train_processed)[:, 1]
train_auc = roc_auc_score(y_train, y_train_proba)

# Test performance
y_test_proba = rf.predict_proba(X_test_processed)[:, 1]
test_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_test_proba)

print("Train AUC:", train_auc)
print("Test AUC:", test_auc)

Train AUC: 0.9875235708115693

In[107]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
scores = cross_val_score(rf, X_train_processed, y_train, cv=5, scoring='roc_auc')
print(f"CV AUC: {scores.mean():.4f} (+/- {scores.std():.4f})")

CV AUC: 0.9869 (+/- 0.0005)

Cross-validation confirms the model's exceptional robustness with an AUC of 98.7% and minimal standard deviation of -/+ 0.0005. The consistency between CV AUC (0.9869), Test AUC (0.9868), and Train AUC (0.9875) demonstrates no overfitting and excellent generalization capability. These results how that our hyperparameter are pretty great choices.

Now that we have a quite robust model, let's dive into it to understand how the different variabels influence the accuracy of it.

Logistic regression as a second model and comparison of the results

In[109]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, roc_curve

# Train Logistic Regression with more iterations and scaled data
lr = LogisticRegression(max_iter=5000, random_state=42, solver='lbfgs')
lr.fit(X_train_processed, y_train)

# Dictionary of models
models = {
    'Random Forest': rf,
    'Logistic Regression': lr
}

# Compare performance
results = []
for name, model in models.items():
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_processed)
    y_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test_processed)[:, 1]
    
    results.append({
        'Model': name,
        'Test AUC': roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba),
        'Accuracy': accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    })

# Display results as DataFrame
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
print(results_df)

                 Model  Test AUC  Accuracy
0        Random Forest  0.986851  0.938130
1  Logistic Regression  0.925513  0.871355

Logistic regression underperforms in capturing the complexity of the data, whereas Random Forest achieves substantially better predictive performance. We therefore keep Random Forest as the final model.

Permutation feature importance (PFI)

In[110]:
from sklearn.inspection import permutation_importance
import pandas as pd

# Compute permutation importance
perm_importance = permutation_importance(
    rf,
    X_test_processed,
    y_test,
    n_repeats=10,
    random_state=42,
    scoring="roc_auc"
)

# Put results in a DataFrame
importances = pd.DataFrame({
    "feature": preprocessor.get_feature_names_out(),
    "importance_mean": perm_importance.importances_mean,
    "importance_std": perm_importance.importances_std
}).sort_values(by="importance_mean", ascending=False)

Permutation importance shows that inflight wifi service, by far, the most influential variable in predicting passenger satisfaction. Permuting this feature leads to the largest decrease in ROC AUC. It means that the model relies a lot on this information to distinguish between satisfied and dissatisfied passengers.

The second most important feature is online boarding, this suggests that the experience before and during the flight is a key driver of satisfaction outcomes overall!

Variables such as type of travel and customer type do not directly represent service quality but capture systematic differences in passenger expectations.

Other service-related variables such as ease of online booking, check-in service, and seat comfort show moderate importance, indicating that satisfaction is driven by a combination of multiple service dimensions rather than a single factor.

This local explanation is particularly interesting. Variables related to travel context, such as business travel or economy class, mainly reflect differences in passenger expectations and slightly reduce the predicted satisfaction score.

However, these effects remain limited compared to the overall impact of service quality.

The SHAP values show that satisfaction is built progressively throughout the entire passenger journey:

  • before the flight, digital services such as online boarding and check in already contribute positively.
  • during the flight, onboard services play a central role, with inflight WiFi standing out as a major driver of satisfaction in this example.
  • after the flight, aspects such as baggage handling and overall service delivery continue to reinforce the positive prediction.

Overall, this example illustrates that passenger satisfaction is not driven by a single element, but by the accumulation of many small service improvements before, during, and after the flight.

Globally, the results show that passenger satisfaction is driven by the quality of core services provided throughout the travel experience.

Online boarding and inflight WiFi appear as the most influential variables, highlighting the importance of smooth digital interactions and connectivity (or simply avoiding checking at airport, which can induce huge queue and stress for passengers).

Other service-related features such as seat comfort, leg room, inflight entertainment, and baggage handling also play a significant role.

Together, these elements contribute to a positive experience before, during, and after the flight, which strongly increases the likelihood of passenger satisfaction.

Conclusions

Overall, this analysis shows that passenger satisfaction is mainly driven by the quality of services provided throughout the entire travel experience.

The results highlight the strong importance of connectivity related features, especially inflight WiFi, which plays a key role in shaping passengers perceptions of the flight. In addition, digital services such as online booking and online boarding significantly contribute to a smoother pre flight experience by reducing waiting times, queues, and stress at the airport.

From a managerial perspective, these findings suggest that airlines could improve passenger satisfaction by investing in better connectivity and higher bandwidth onboard, as well as by further digitalizing the reservation and check in processes.

Overall, enhancing both connectivity and digital touchpoints appears to be an effective strategy to improve the end to end passenger experience and increase overall satisfaction.

Limits of the model

It would have been interesting to split the dataset to see the key features needed to increase the likelihood to customers to be satisfied regarding their class (business and economics). We can assume that depending on the class, the expectations of passengers can differ.
